<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-06-04T01:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-06-04T01:00:00-05:00" n="389" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d389">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00111A Recruiting/224:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Lockhart</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-06-04T15:00:00+09:00">June
                                        4, 1941—3 p.m.</date>
                                    <lb/> [Received 11:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>650. The Department’s instructions are respectfully requested as to
                                whether, in view of the provisions of the Neutrality Act,<note n="11" xml:id="d389fn11">Approved November 4, 1939; 54 Stat.
                                    4.</note> neutrality proclamation as published in Radio Bulletin
                                No. 209, September 5, 1939,<note n="12" xml:id="d389fn12">See
                                    Department of State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, September
                                    9, 1939, p. 203.</note> and other provisions of law, the
                                enlistment in China (with its extraterritorial aspects) of American
                                citizens in the British armed forces is a lawful act, those
                                Americans upon enlistment presumably to proceed ultimately to combat
                                zones.</p>
                            <p>Sent to the Department. Repeated to Chungking and Peiping.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Lockhart</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>